data.content:
All four areas you described are affected by .NET 11 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

### 1. GZipStream empty-payload check ⚠️ **Behavioral**
In .NET 11, `GZipStream` now writes valid headers/footers even when no data is written. Your zero-length check will **never trigger** anymore.

**Fix:** Check the uncompressed byte count instead of output stream length:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 10): ms.Length == 0 meant "no data"
// After (.NET 11): ms.Length > 0 always (headers/footers written)

// Fix: track whether you actually wrote any data
bool wroteData = false;
using (var gz = new GZipStream(ms, CompressionMode.Compress, leaveOpen: true))
{
    if (hasData) { gz.Write(data); wroteData = true; }
}
if (!wroteData) { /* handle "no data" */ }
```

---

### 2. TAR header checksum validation ⚠️ **Behavioral**
TAR-reading APIs now **verify checksums**. Hand-crafted archives with invalid checksums will **throw at read time**.

**Fix:** Add error handling, or fix the legacy tool's output:
```csharp
try
{
    using var reader = new TarReader(stream);
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry(); // throws on bad checksum
}
catch (InvalidDataException ex)
{
    // Handle legacy TAR files with invalid checksums
}
```

---

### 3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading ⚠️ **Behavioral**
`ZipArchive.CreateAsync` now **eagerly loads** all entries instead of lazy loading. For large ZIP files this increases **peak memory usage**.

**Fix:** Be aware of the higher memory footprint. For very large archives, consider streaming approaches or processing entries in smaller batches.

---

### 4. MemoryStream maximum capacity ⚠️ **Behavioral**
The maximum capacity and exception behavior for `MemoryStream` changed. Allocations near the old limit may now throw **different exception types** or at **different thresholds**.

**Fix:** Review code that creates very large `MemoryStream` instances or catches specific exception types (`OutOfMemoryException`, `IOException`) related to capacity limits. Update catch blocks and capacity assumptions.

---

### TFM Update

Don't forget the basic project file change:
```xml
<!-- Before -->
<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
<!-- After -->
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
```

The **TAR checksum** and **GZipStream empty-payload** changes are most likely to cause silent bugs or runtime failures in your app. I'd prioritize those two.
